  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6c4d1473-418a-45df-b3c1-102679a88a33",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Column Descriptions\n",
    "- fixed acidity: Concentration of non-volatile acids (mainly tartaric acid); contributes to the wine’s stability and taste.\n",
    "- volatile acidity: Amount of acetic acid; high levels can give wine an unpleasant vinegar flavor.\n",
    "- citric acid: Adds freshness and flavor; low levels may make wine taste flat.\n",
    "- residual sugar: Sugar remaining after fermentation; affects sweetness and mouthfeel.\n",
    "- chlorides: Salt content; influences taste and preservation.\n",
    "- free sulfur dioxide: SO₂ not bound to other compounds; protects against microbial growth and oxidation.\n",
    "- total sulfur dioxide: Total SO₂ (free + bound); excessive amounts can affect taste and consumer health.\n",
    "- density: Related to sugar and alcohol content; used to monitor fermentation.\n",
    "- pH: Measures acidity; lower pH means higher acidity.\n",
    "- sulphates: Add to wine’s antimicrobial stability and can enhance flavor.\n",
    "- alcohol: Percentage of alcohol by volume; often correlates with perceived quality.\n",
    "- quality: Sensory score (typically 0–10) given by wine experts; target variable for prediction.\n"
   ]
  },
